# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asc-x9
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:asc-x9/american-national-standards-institute] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] This city served as the seat of the Confederation Congress, formerly the Second Continental Congress, and temporary national capital of the United States in 1783–1784.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] At that time, General George Washington came before the body convened in the new Maryland State House and resigned his commission as commander of the Continental Army.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] A month later, the Congress ratified the Treaty of Paris of 1783, ending the American Revolutionary War, with Great Britain recognizing the independence of the United States.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The city and state capitol was also the site of the 1786 Annapolis Convention, which issued a call to the states to send delegates for the Constitutional Convention to be held the following year in Philadelphia.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Annapolis Peace Conference took place in 2007.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Naval Academy, established 1845, is adjacent to the city limits.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The settlers later moved to a better-protected harbor on the Severn's southern shore.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The settlement on the south shore, known from 1683 as "Town at Proctor's", then "Town at the Severn", became in 1694 "Anne Arundel's Towne" (after Lady Anne Arundell (1616–1649), the late wife of the late Cecilius Calvert, second Lord Baltimore, 1605–1675).
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] In 1654, after the Third English Civil War, Parliamentary forces assumed control of the Maryland colony and Stone went into exile south across the Potomac River in Virginia.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Per orders from Lord Baltimore, Stone returned the following spring at the head of a Cavalier royalist force, loyal to the uncrowned King of England.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] On March 25, 1655, in what became known as the Battle of the Severn (the first colonial naval battle in North America), Stone was defeated, taken prisoner, and replaced by Lt.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Josias Fendall (1628–1687) as fifth Proprietary Governor.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Fendall governed Maryland during the latter half of the English Commonwealth period.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] In 1660, he was replaced by Phillip Calvert (1626–1682) as fifth/sixth Governor of Maryland, after the restoration of Charles II (1630–1685) as King in England.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Annapolis was incorporated as a city in 1708.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Colonel John Seymour, the Governor of Maryland from 1704 to 1709, wrote Queen Anne on March 16, 1709, with qualifications for municipal officials and provisions for fairs and market days for the town.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] In the 17th century, Annapolis was little more than a village, but it grew rapidly for most of the 18th century until the American Revolutionary War as a political and administrative capital, a port of entry, and a major center of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The *Maryland Gazette*, which became an important weekly journal, was founded there by Jonas Green in 1745; in 1769 a theater opened; during this period also the commerce was considerable, but it declined rapidly after Baltimore, with its deeper harbor, was made a port of entry in 1780.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Water trades such as oyster-packing, boatbuilding and sailmaking became the city's chief industries.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Annapolis is home to a large number of recreational boats that have largely replaced the seafood industry in the city.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] ) was built in 1735 and is the oldest extant government building in Annapolis.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Alexander Hamilton (1712–1756), a Scottish-born doctor and writer, lived and worked in Annapolis.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Leo Lemay says his 1744 travel diary *Gentleman's Progress: The Itinerarium of Dr.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Annapolis became the temporary capital of the United States after the signing of the Treaty of Paris in 1783.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Congress was in session in the state house from November 26, 1783, to August 19, 1784, and it was in Annapolis on December 23, 1783, that General Washington resigned his commission as commander-in-chief of the Continental Army.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] For the 1783 Congress, the Governor of Maryland commissioned John Shaw, a local cabinetmaker, to create an American flag.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Shaw's flag is slightly different from other designs of the time: the blue field extends over the entire height of the hoist.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Shaw developed two versions of the flag: one which started with a red stripe and another that started with a white one.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] In 1786, delegates from all states of the Union were invited to meet in Annapolis to consider measures for the better regulation of commerce.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Delegates from only five states—New York, Pennsylvania, Virginia, New Jersey, and Delaware—actually attended the September 1786 gathering, known afterward as the Annapolis Convention.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Without proceeding to the business for which they had met, the delegates passed a resolution calling for another convention to meet at Philadelphia in the following year to amend the Articles of Confederation.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The resulting Philadelphia Convention drafted and approved the Constitution of the United States, which remains in force.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] On April 24, 1861, the midshipmen of the Naval Academy relocated their base in Annapolis and were temporarily housed in Newport, Rhode Island, until October 1865.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] In 1861, the first of three camps that were built for holding paroled soldiers was created on the campus of St.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The second location of Camp Parole would house over 20,000 and would be located where Forest Drive is currently.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The third and final location was finished in late 1863 and would be placed near the Elkridge Railroad, as to make transportation of soldiers and resources easier before and allowing the camp to grow to its highest numbers.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] This area just west of the city is still referred to as Parole.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The soldiers who did not survive were buried in the Annapolis National Cemetery.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] In 1900, Annapolis had a population of 8,585.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] On December 21, 1906, Henry Davis was lynched in the city.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] He was suspected of assaulting a local woman.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] During World War II, shipyards in Annapolis built a number of PT Boats, and military vessels such as minesweepers and patrol boats were built in Annapolis during the Korean and Vietnam wars.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] It was at Annapolis in July 1940 that Grand Duchess Charlotte of Luxembourg arrived in exile during World War II.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] In the summer of 1984, the Navy Marine Corps Memorial Stadium in Annapolis hosted soccer games as part of the XXIII Olympiad.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] During September 18–19, 2003, Hurricane Isabel created the largest storm surge known in Annapolis's history, cresting at 7.58 feet (2.31 m).
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Much of downtown Annapolis was flooded and many businesses and homes in outlying areas were damaged.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The previous record was 6.35 feet (1.94 m) during a hurricane in 1933, and 5.5 feet (1.7 m) during Hurricane Hazel in 1954.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Downtown Annapolis has high-tide "sunny day" flooding.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] A Stanford University study found that this resulted in 3,000 fewer visits and $172,000 in lost revenue for local business in 2017.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] From mid-2007 through December 2008, the city celebrated the 300th anniversary of its 1708 Royal Charter, which established democratic self-governance.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The many cultural events of this celebration were organized by Annapolis Charter 300.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Annapolis was home of the Anne Arundel County Battle of the Bands, which was held at Maryland Hall from 1999 to 2015.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The event was a competition between musical groups from each high school in the county; it raised over $100,000 for the county's high school music programs during its 17-year run.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] On June 28, 2018, at the Capital Gazette, a gunman killed five journalists and injured two more.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] An EF-2 tornado struck the western edge of the city on September 1, 2021, during the remnants of Hurricane Ida.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Homes, businesses, and restaurants had significant damage near Maryland Route 450, where EF-2 damage was observed with estimated winds of 125 mph (201 km/h).
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The tornado dissipated immediately past U.S.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The conference was held at the United States Naval Academy on November 26, 2007.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Maryland State House is the oldest in continuous legislative use in the United States.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Construction started in 1772, and the Maryland legislature first met there in 1779.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] It is topped by the largest wooden dome built without nails in the country.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Maryland State House housed the workings of the United States government from November 26, 1783, to August 13, 1784, and the Treaty of Paris was ratified there on January 14, 1784, so Annapolis became the first peacetime capital of the U.S.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] It was in the Maryland State House that George Washington famously resigned his commission before the Continental Congress on December 23, 1783.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The United States Naval Academy was founded in 1845 on the site of Fort Severn, and now occupies an area of land reclaimed from the Severn River.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Students who attend the Naval Academy are enrolled for four years with a following five-year commitment to serving on active duty in the Marine Corps or Navy.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Students hold the naval rank of midshipman, and on average about 4,500 are enrolled.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] John's College is a non-sectarian private college that was once supported by the state.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] It was opened in 1789 as the successor of King William's School, which was founded by an act of the Maryland legislature in 1696 and was opened in 1701.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Its principal building, McDowell Hall, was originally to be the governor's mansion; although £4,000 was appropriated to build it in 1742, it was not completed until after the War of Independence.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Located 25 miles (40 km) south of Baltimore and 30 miles (48 km) east of Washington, D.C., Annapolis is the closest state capital to the national capital.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] In land area Annapolis (proper) is also the smallest of the United States capital cities.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The city is a part of the Atlantic Coastal Plain, and is relatively flat, with the highest point being only 50 feet (15 m) above sea level.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 8.10 square miles (20.98 km2), of which 7.18 square miles (18.60 km2) is land and 0.92 square miles (2.38 km2) is water.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Annapolis lies within the humid subtropical climate zone (Köppen: *Cfa*), with hot, humid summers (up to 30°C/86°F), cool winters (low as -1.2°C/29.8°F), and generous precipitation (ranges from 60 millimeters/2.38 inches to 131 millimeters/5.14 inches) year-round.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Low elevation and proximity to the Chesapeake Bay give the area more moderate spring and summertime temperatures and slightly less extreme winter lows than locations further inland, such as Washington, D.C.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] cm) over the course of a single century.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] In November 2020, NASA reported that Annapolis had 18 days of high-tide (non-storm-related) flooding from May 2019 to April 2020, an increase over 2018's 12 days, and higher than the 1995-2005 average of 2 days annually.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The increase is attributed to sea level rise caused by climate change.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Resultant flood damages caused local businesses to lose as much as $172,000 a year.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] On Naval Academy grounds, seawater came out of storm drains, with McNair Road and Ramsay Road flooding 20 times in 2020 and more than 40 times each in 2018 and 2019.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Though a $37 million sea wall was completed in 2024 to adapt to flooding occurring 30 to 40 times a year, adaptation approaches such as sea walls and building up the height of roadways and athletic fields are predicted to be effective for only a few decades.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Annapolis has seen the highest increased rate of coastal flooding in the country.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Naval Academy is especially vulnerable to sea rise, as it is surrounded on three sides by water, and has some land only three feet above the 2019 water line.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Hurricanes—which have been increasing in intensity because of global warming—pose additional flooding threats, with Hurricane Isabel having caused $100 million in flood damage in 2003.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Academy's Sea Level Rise Advisory Council has created a climate change adaptation plan including seawall repair, door dams, doorway barriers, backflow preventers in storm drain systems, and elevated building entrances.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] After 2024's record 120 flooding events, on November 3, 2025, ground was broken on an $87 million City Dock Project designed to protect against expected flooding events through 2060.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Specifically, the goal is to protect against flood waters up to 8.77 feet (2.67 m) above the daily average lowest level of the water—higher than the 7.2 feet (2.2 m) experienced during 2003's Hurricane Isabel.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The plan involves adding floodgates, raising land to block rising water levels, installing a park, and constructing a Maritime Welcome Center.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] As of the 2020 census, Annapolis had a population of 40,812.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] 21.6% of residents were under the age of 18 and 16.3% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] For every 100 females there were 90.5 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 86.6 males age 18 and over.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] There were 16,751 households in Annapolis, of which 27.3% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Of all households, 36.8% were married-couple households, 19.5% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 36.0% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] About 33.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 12.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] There were 18,455 housing units, of which 9.2% were vacant.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.9% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.1%.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] As of the census of 2010, there were 38,394 people, 16,136 households, and 8,776 families residing in the city.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The population density was 5,347.4 inhabitants per square mile (2,064.6/km2).
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] There were 17,845 housing units at an average density of 2,485.4 units per square mile (959.6 units/km2).
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The racial makeup of the city was 60.1% White, 26.0% African American, 0.3% Native American, 2.1% Asian, 9.0% from other races, and 2.6% from two or more races.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Hispanic or Latino people of any race were 16.8% of the population.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] There were 16,136 households, of which 26.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 35.3% were married couples living together, 14.9% had a female householder with no husband present, 4.2% had a male householder with no wife present, and 45.6% were non-families.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Of all households, 35.0% were made up of individuals, and 11.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The average household size was 2.34 and the average family size was 3.02.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The median age in the city was 36 years.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] 20.8% of residents were under the age of 18; 9.9% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 31.1% were from 25 to 44; 25.3% were from 45 to 64; and 13% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The gender makeup of the city was 47.8% male and 52.2% female.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] As of the census of 2000, there were 35,838 people, 15,303 households, and 8,676 families residing in the city.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The population density was 5,326.0 inhabitants per square mile (2,056.4/km2).
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] There were 16,165 housing units at an average density of 2,402.3 units per square mile (927.5 units/km2).
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The racial makeup of the city was 62.66% White, 31.44% Black or African American, 0.17% Native American, 1.81% Asian, 0.03% Pacific Islander, 2.22% from other races, and 1.67% from two or more races.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] 8.42% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] There were 15,303 households, out of which 24.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 36.6% were married couples living together, 16.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 43.3% were non-families.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Of all households, 32.9% were made up of individuals, and 9.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The average household size was 2.30 and the average family size was 2.93.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] For every 100 females, there were 90.0 males.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] For every 100 females age 18 and over there were 86.8 males age 18 and over.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The median income for a household in the city was $49,243, and the median income for a family was $56,984 (these figures had risen to $70,140 and $84,573 respectively, according to a 2007 estimate).
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Males had a median income of $39,548 versus $30,741 for females.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The per capita income for the city was $27,180.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] About 9.5% of families and 12.7% of the population were living in poverty, of which 20.8% were under age 18 and 10.4% were age 65 or over.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Annapolis has a thriving community theater scene which includes two venues in the historic district.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] On East Street, Colonial Players produces approximately six shows a year in its 180-seat theater.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] *A Christmas Carol* has been a seasonal tradition in Annapolis since it opened at the Colonial Players theater in 1981.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Based on the play by Charles Dickens, the 90-minute production by the Colonial Players is an original musical adaptation, with play and lyrics by Richard Wade and music by Dick Gessner.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Colonial Players, Inc. is a nonprofit organization founded in 1949.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Its first production, *The Male Animal*, was performed in 1949 at the Annapolis Recreation Center on Compromise Street.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] In 1955, the organization moved to its venue in a former automotive repair shop on East Street.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] During the warmer months, Annapolis Summer Garden Theatre presents three shows on its outdoor stage, which is visible from the City Dock.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] A nonprofit organization, Annapolis Summer Garden Theatre has been providing "theatre under the stars" since 1966, when it performed *You Can't Take It with You* and *Brigadoon* at Carvel Hall Hotel.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] It began leasing its site at 143 Compromise Street, the former location of the Shaw Blacksmith Shop, in 1967, and became owner of the property in 1990.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Naval Academy Masqueraders, a theater group at the United States Naval Academy, produces one "main-stage show" each fall and student-directed one-act plays in the spring.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Founded in 1847, the Masqueraders is the oldest extracurricular activity at the Naval Academy.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Its shows, performed in Mahan Hall, are selected to support the academy's English curriculum.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The King William Players, a student theater group at St.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] John's College, holds two performances each semester in the college's Francis Scott Key Auditorium.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Admission is usually free and open to the public.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Banneker-Douglass Museum, located in the historic Mount Moriah Church at 87 Franklin Street, documents the history of African Americans in Maryland.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Since its opening on February 24, 1984, the museum has provided educational programs, rotating exhibits, and a research facility.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Preble Hall, named for Edward Preble, houses the United States Naval Academy Museum, founded in 1845.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Robinson Collection contains 6,000 prints depicting European and American naval history from 1514 through World War II.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] It is also home to one of the world's best ship model collections, donated by Henry Huttleston Rogers.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Rogers's donation was the impetus for the construction of Preble Hall.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The museum has approximately 100,000 visitors each year.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Hammond-Harwood House, located at 19 Maryland Avenue, was built in 1774 for Matthias Hammond, a wealthy Maryland farmer.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Its design was adapted by William Buckland from Andrea Palladio's Villa Pisani to accommodate American Colonial regional preferences.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Since 1940, when the house was purchased from St.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] John's College by the Hammond-Harwood House Association, it has served as a museum exhibiting a collection of John Shaw furniture and Charles Willson Peale paintings.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Its exterior and interior preserve the original architecture of a mansion from the late Colonial period.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Annapolis City Dock lies at the foot of Main Street that slopes down from Church Circle and St.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The dock is now a narrow waterway from Spa Creek, once named Carrol's Creek with the dock area called Dock Cove, into the heart of the lower town.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] At the head of the dock is a small park with the Kunta Kinte-Alex Haley Memorial with the Market House and a traffic circle in an expanse of asphalt surrounded by historic buildings.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Market House, though relatively modern, stands in a vicinity occupied by similar market houses dating to 1730 when the city market was moved from the State House area to the head of the dock.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The dock itself is now used largely by recreational vessels rather than the commercial boats and boats of Chesapeake Bay watermen selling catches.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The dock and surroundings are part of the Colonial Annapolis National Historic Landmark (NHL) District.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Kunta Kinte-Alex Haley memorial, located in a park at the head of Annapolis City Dock, commemorates the arrival point of Alex Haley's African ancestor, Kunta Kinte, whose story is related in Haley's 1976 novel *Roots: The Saga of an American Family*.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] A sculpture group at the memorial site portrays Alex Haley seated, reading from a book to three children.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The final phase of the memorial's construction was completed in 2002.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Paca House and Garden encompasses an 18th-century Georgian mansion constructed by William Paca, a signer of the Declaration of Independence.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The property includes a terraced garden that has been restored to its colonial-era design.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Annapolis often serves as the end point for the 3,000-mile annual transcontinental Race Across America bicycle race.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] To the north of the state house is a monument to Thurgood Marshall, the first black justice of the US Supreme Court and formerly a Maryland lawyer who won many important civil rights cases.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Located just before the Naval Academy Bridge is the World War II Memorial, which was constructed in 1998 to symbolize the sacrifice made by the 275,000 citizens from Maryland who joined the service to fight in the war.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The memorial is composed of 48 granite columns to represent the 48 states at the time of the war surrounding an amphitheater in which are the names of 6,454 men who gave their lives in the war.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Directly behind the memorial are both the Maryland, and United States flags, and a star shaped column with a seven sided base to represent Maryland being the seventh state in the Union.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] On March 9, 2010, the Chesapeake Bayhawks of Major League Lacrosse moved from Washington, D.C., to the Annapolis area, at Navy–Marine Corps Memorial Stadium.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] In 2013, the Bayhawks won the league's championship, the Steinfeld Cup, for the fifth time.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Annapolis Blues FC is a men's amateur soccer team that plays in USL League Two, which also competes out of Navy–Marine Corps Memorial Stadium.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The city boasts over 200 acres (81 ha) of parkland, with the largest being the 70-acre (28 ha) Truxtun Heights Park.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Quiet Waters Park, a 340-acre (140 ha) regional park run by Anne Arundel County, offers water access, a playground area, over 6 miles (9.7 km) of paved trails, and ice skating rink, and a dog beach.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Annapolis is home to many seasonal or holiday-themed events and festivals that take place throughout the year.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Patrick's Day Parade, May Day, and United States Naval Academy Commissioning Week.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Annapolis is governed via the weak mayor system.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The city council consists of eight aldermen who are elected from single-member wards.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The mayor is elected directly in a citywide vote.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Since 2008, several aldermen have introduced unsuccessful charter amendments to institute a council–manager system, a move opposed by both Democratic mayor Joshua J.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Cohen and his Republican successor Mike Pantelides.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The state legislature, governor's office, and appellate courts are located in Annapolis.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] While Annapolis is the state's only capital, some administrative offices, including a number of cabinet-level departments, are based in Baltimore.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Annapolis is served by the Anne Arundel County Public Schools system.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Founded in 1896, Annapolis High School has an internationally recognized IB International Program.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Anne's School of Annapolis, Aleph Bet Jewish Day School, Annapolis Area Christian School, St.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Martins Lutheran School, Severn School, St.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Mary's High School (Annapolis, Maryland), and Indian Creek School are private schools in the Annapolis area.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Key School, located on a converted farm in the neighborhood of Hillsmere, has also served Annapolis for over 50 years.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Anne Arundel County's alternative school, Mary E.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Moss Academy, which has around 160 students ranging grades 6–9, is also in the Annapolis area.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] No major highways enter the city limits of Annapolis.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Just outside the city limits, I-595/US 50/US 301 traverses the region on an east–west route, connecting the Annapolis area to Washington, D.C., and the Eastern Shore of Maryland.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] I-97 interchanges with I-595/US 50/US 301 a few miles west of Annapolis and provides the most direct link to Baltimore.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] MD 2 also passes just outside the city limits and is the best connection to Southern Maryland, while also providing an alternate route to Baltimore.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The most prominent roads directly accessing the city include MD 70, which connects downtown Annapolis to US 50/US 301, and MD 665, which does likewise for the southwestern portions of the city.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Other state highways serving Annapolis include MD 181, MD 387, MD 393, MD 435, MD 436, MD 450, MD 788 and MD 797.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Annapolis Department of Transportation provides bus service with eight routes, collectively branded Annapolis Transit.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The system serves the city with recreational areas, shopping centers, educational and medical facilities, and employment hubs.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] ADOT also offers transportation for the elderly and persons with disabilities.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Several Maryland Transit Administration commuter buses also allow for access to Baltimore or Washington, D.C.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] From 1840 to 1968, Annapolis was connected to the outside world by railroad.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The Washington, Baltimore and Annapolis Electric Railway operated two electrified interurban lines that brought passengers into the city from both the South and the North.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The southern route ran down King George Street and Main Street, leading directly to the statehouse, while the northern route entered town via Glen Burnie.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] In 1935, the Washington, Baltimore and Annapolis Electric Railway went bankrupt due to the effects of the Great Depression and suspended service along its southern route, while the newly created Baltimore & Annapolis Railroad retained service on the northern route.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Steam trains of the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad also occasionally operated over the line to Annapolis, primarily for special Naval Academy movements.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] Passenger rail service on the Baltimore & Annapolis Railroad was eventually discontinued in 1950; freight service ceased in 1968 after the dilapidated trestle crossing the Severn River was condemned.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The tracks were eventually dismantled in 1976.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The 1992 film *Patriot Games* is filmed in part in Annapolis, particularly around the USNA.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The 1955 film *An Annapolis Story* takes place at the U.S.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The 2006 film *Annapolis* is set in the titular city.
[src:asc-x9/annapolis-maryland] The 2014 film *Are You Here* is partially set in Annapolis.
[src:asc-x9/asc-x9] The **Accredited Standards Committee X9** (ASC X9, Inc.) is an ANSI (American National Standards Institute) accredited standards developing organization, responsible for developing voluntary open consensus standards for the financial services industry in the U.S.
[src:asc-x9/asc-x9] Membership in ASC X9 is open to all U.S. domiciled companies and organizations in the financial services industry.
[src:asc-x9/asc-x9] The committee was founded in 1974 under the American National Standards Institute, to develop financial industry standards following a surge in electronic banking, automated clearing, and data security needs.
[src:asc-x9/asc-x9] In 1984 it played a major role role in supporting the Check Clearing for the 21st Century Act (Check 21) through development of check image exchange and related standards.
[src:asc-x9/asc-x9] In the 1990s it expanded its cryptography standards, developing foundational specifications for secure data exchange and public key infrastructures (e.g., X9.42, X9.73, X9.24).
[src:asc-x9/asc-x9] In 2001, the organization was incorporated as ASC X9, Inc., transitioning from a pure ANSI committee to a non-profit industry consortium still accredited by ANSI.
[src:asc-x9/asc-x9] During the 2000s and 2010s it joined with international bodies like ISO/TC 68, helping shape ISO 20022 and other global standards for payments and securities messaging.
[src:asc-x9/asc-x9] The Accredited Standards Committee X9 develops, establishes, maintains, and promotes standards for the Financial Services Industry in the United States in order to facilitate delivery of financial services and products.
[src:asc-x9/austrian-standards-international] The first standard was published in 1921 on metric screw threads.
[src:asc-x9/austrian-standards-international] In 1932, the committee's name was shortened to the *Österreichischer Normenausschuss* (Austrian Standards Committee).
[src:asc-x9/austrian-standards-international] With the Austrian *Anschluss* to Nazi Germany in 1938, it became a branch office of the German *Deutsches Institut für Normung* (DIN) standards organization, but resumed operations in its own right after World War II, and was a founding ISO member in 1946.
[src:asc-x9/austrian-standards-international] The 1954 Federal Act on Standardization recognized the activities of the committee, and the Act, as amended, serves as its legal basis.
[src:asc-x9/austrian-standards-international] The Austrian Standards Committee's name was changed to *ON Österreichisches Normungsinstitut* in 1969.
[src:asc-x9/austrian-standards-international] On 1 March 2006, the Institute published ON rule ONR 168000, used to calculate the monetary value of a brand.
[src:asc-x9/austrian-standards-international] In 2018, the name was changed to Austrian Standards International.
[src:asc-x9/austrian-standards-international] The Institute is located at Heinestrasse 38, 1020 Vienna.
[src:asc-x9/austrian-standards-international] The acronym ÖNORM designates a national standard published by the Austrian Standards International and applicable to Austria alone.
[src:asc-x9/austrian-standards-international] Austrian national standards have the acronym "ÖNORM" followed by one letter and a unique number.
[src:asc-x9/austrian-standards-international] In the examples above, the letter "S" following "ÖNORM" indicates that these standards address topics not covered elsewhere (*Sonstige Normengebiete* in German).
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The **National Standardization Agency** of Indonesia (Indonesian: *Badan Standardisasi Nasional*; **BSN**) is the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) member body for Indonesia.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] BSN is a non-ministerial Indonesian government agency with the main task of carrying out governmental tasks in the field of standardization and conformity assessment in Indonesia.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The agency is also responsible to develop and maintain the Indonesian National Standard.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Actively involved in various International Organizations such as ISO, IEC, CAC, APEC, APLAC, ILAC, PAC, ASEAN, and so on.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Active participation of BSN can be in the form of attending international standard formulation sessions in order to fight for the interests of Indonesia, as well as hosting the session / hosting.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Encouraging the central government, regional governments, associations, industry, and universities to participate actively in developing and promoting SNI.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The efforts of BSN to encourage stakeholders to jointly conduct standardization and conformity assessment activities, are formally formulated through the signing of the Cooperation Text (MOU).
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Conducting research and testing of SNI products in the market, of which the results can be inputs for relevant Ministries that have the capacity to be market supervisors.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The research activities conducted by BSN can also be included for SNI development and maintenance activities.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Organizing National Standards of Measurement Unit that enable metrological activities in Indonesia to be recognized by the world.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Implementation of guidance and general administrative services in the fields of general planning, administration, organization and governance, staffing, finance, filing, coding, equipment and household.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 5. organizing education and training in its fields.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The establishment of BSN is closely related to the long history of standardization in Indonesia.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The development and application of standards began during the Dutch and Japanese colonial periods and continued after Indonesia declared independence and became officially sovereign.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Standardization was initially used to support colonial economic activities and ensure their smooth operation.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Dutch engineers, who were mostly civil engineers, began to set standards for building materials, transportation equipment, and electrical installation standards, as well as requirements for external lines.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] During World War II and the Japanese occupation (1942-1945), formal standardization activities were halted.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] However, on August 17, 1945, Indonesia proclaimed its independence.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The country immediately formed a government and planned for development to improve the standard of living and welfare of the people, with the goal of achieving equality with other countries.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1951 the amendment to the "Raad Normalization" statute was formed and the Indonesian Normalization Fund Foundation (YDNI) was formed.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1955 YDNI represented Indonesia as a member of the ISO international standards organization and in 1966 YDNI successfully represented Indonesia as a member of the International Electrotechnical Commission / IEC.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] It turns out that this law has not been able to be a means of managing overall standardization activities.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The government began to place standardization as a strategic function in supporting national development.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1973, the "National System Development for Standardization" program was established as a priority.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1976, the National Standardization System Preparation Committee was formed.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1984, with the Decree of the President of the Republic of Indonesia the National Standardization Board (DSN) was formed with the main task of establishing standardization policies, coordinating and fostering cooperation in the field of national standardization.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The Chairperson of the National Standardization Board is held by the State Minister for Research and Technology, Prof.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Through the struggle of the previous leadership, Alm.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Herudi Kartowisastro, on March 27, 1997, the government dissolved the DSN which subsequently changed to the National Standardization Body.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] BSN itself is a Non-Ministry Government Institution (LPNK) that is given the task by the government to foster and coordinate all standardization and conformity assessment activities in Indonesia.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The establishment of BSN was based on Presidential Decree No.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 13 of 1997 perfected by Presidential Decree No.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 166 of 2000 concerning Position, Duties, Functions, Authority, Organizational Structure and Work Procedures of Non-Departmental Government Institutions as amended several times, and the most recent by Presidential Decree No.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 4 of 2018, concerning the National Standardization Agency.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In order to enhance the development of the Indonesian National Standard (SNI), the government established Government Regulation No.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 102 of 2000 concerning National Standardization.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 20 of 2014 concerning Standardization and Conformity Assessment was stipulated.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] With the existence of this Law, the government will further strengthen the existence and role of BSN in the development process in Indonesia both in the context of physical development, efficient management of natural resources, and the development of highly competitive Indonesian people.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Welcoming the era of globalization which demands high competitiveness, as well as the implementation of Law No.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 20 of 2014, the BSN successfully reorganized itself to include a new structure namely the Deputy for the National Standard Measuring Unit (SNSU) in 2018.
[src:asc-x9/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The chairman of BSN is under and directly responsible to the President of Indonesia.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The origins of the Bangladesh Standards and Testing Institution (BSTI) can be traced back to the mid-20th century during the period of East Pakistan.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] In 1955, a regional branch of the Central Testing Laboratories (CTL) was established in Dhaka to assess the quality of imported and domestically produced goods.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] This was followed by the establishment of a regional office of the Pakistan Standards Institution in Dhaka in 1957, and the creation of the Certification Marks Inspectorate in Chittagong in 1963 to regulate industrial product certification.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Following Bangladesh's independence in 1971, the Bangladesh Standards Institution (BDSI) was formed as the country's national standards body.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] It became a member of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1974.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] In an effort to consolidate standards development, testing, and certification functions, the government enacted Ordinance No.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] XXXVII of 1985, merging BDSI and CTL to form the present-day Bangladesh Standards and Testing Institution (BSTI).
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The institution's scope was further expanded in 1995 with the merger of the Department of Agricultural Grading and Marking.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Earlier, in 1982, the Standards of Weights and Measures Ordinance was promulgated to implement the metric system across the country, a function now overseen by BSTI.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI operates under the Ministry of Industries and serves as the national authority for standardization, conformity assessment, and metrology.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Over the years, it has undergone significant modernization.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] A National Metrology Laboratory was established with financial and technical assistance from the European Union, NORAD, UNIDO, and the Government of Bangladesh.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI's laboratories—covering physical, chemical, and microbiological testing—have received accreditation from the National Accreditation Board for Testing and Calibration Laboratories (NABL) of India.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Its product certification scheme is accredited by the National Accreditation Board for Certification Bodies (NABCB) of India.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The Management System Certification (MSC) program has also been accredited by both Norwegian Accreditation and the Bangladesh Accreditation Board (BAB).
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] In recent years, BSTI expanded its infrastructure with the inauguration of a modern testing facility in Khulna on 21 November 2023, followed by the opening of a ten-story center in Chittagong's Agrabad Commercial Area on 28 June 2025.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The Chittagong facility, equipped with advanced laboratories, aims to bolster the region's role as a major port and industrial hub by strengthening BSTI's capabilities in product testing, certification, and trade facilitation.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The responsibility of promulgating these standards lies with the Bangladesh Standards and Testing Institution (BSTI), while the task of technical drafting and declaration is carried out by the BCC.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The organization has already developed several standards and simultaneously modernized the existing ones.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Due to lack of coherence and synergy between vendors and technologists, these standards were largely never widely accepted nor recognized by international bodies.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Later, versions of standards such as BSCII in essence rubber stamped Unicode encoding scheme.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] An official order to mandatorily install a keyboard layout package kit in 2018 spawned furor over multiple fronts.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI is the national standards body of Bangladesh, responsible for formulating and issuing Bangladesh Standards (BDS) for products, services, and processes.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Since its establishment, BSTI has developed over 4,000 standards to ensure quality, safety, and compliance.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] It certifies products that meet national standards by issuing a Certification Mark (CM) licence, valid for three years, following thorough factory inspections and laboratory testing.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Use of the BSTI certification mark is restricted to licensed manufacturers.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Currently, 315 products require mandatory CM licences for domestic production, distribution, and sale, while 79 imported items need BSTI clearance under the country's import policy.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI's Metrology Division regulates packaged commodities under the *Package Commodity Registration Rules 2021* and calibrates weighing and measuring devices to ensure adherence to the International System of Units.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The institution also provides laboratory testing and calibration services to industries, markets, government offices, and individuals.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Its monitoring activities include market surveillance, mobile courts, and random sampling from markets and factories to combat substandard or counterfeit goods.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Additionally, BSTI represents Bangladesh in international and regional standards organizations and promotes public awareness of quality standards and consumer rights.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI is an autonomous agency of the Government of Bangladesh.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] It operates its activities under the *Bangladesh Standards & Testing Institution Act - 2018*.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] A counsel of 37 members is the decision-making body of the institution.
[src:asc-x9/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Minister for the Ministry of Industries is the chairperson of the counsel.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] The **British Standards Institution** (**BSI**) is the national standards body of the United Kingdom.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] BSI produces technical standards on a wide range of products and services and also supplies standards certification services for business and personnel.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] BSI was founded as the Engineering Standards Committee in London in 1901.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] It subsequently extended its standardization work and became the British Engineering Standards Association in 1918, adopting the name British Standards Institution in 1931 after receiving a Royal Charter in 1929.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] In 1998, a revision of the Charter enabled the organization to diversify and acquire other businesses, and the trading name was changed to BSI Group.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] The Group now operates in 195 countries.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] The core business remains standards and standards related services, although the majority of the Group's revenue comes from management systems assessment and certification work.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI appointed its first female chief executive officer, Susan Taylor Martin.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] BSI produces British Standards, and, as the UK's National Standards Body, is also responsible for the UK publication, in English, of international and European standards.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] BSI is obliged to adopt and publish all European Standards as identical British Standards (prefixed BS EN) and to withdraw pre-existing British Standards that are in conflict.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] However, it has the option to adopt and publish international standards (prefixed BS ISO or BS IEC).
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] In response to commercial demands, BSI also produces commissioned standards products such as Publicly Available Specifications (PASs), Private Standards and Business Information Publications.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] These products are commissioned by individual organizations and trade associations to meet their needs for standardized specifications, guidelines, codes of practice etc.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] Because they are not subject to the same consultation and consensus requirements as formal standards, the lead time is shorter.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] BSI also publishes standards-related books, CD-ROMs, subscription and web-based products as well as providing training on standards-related issues.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] With 80,000 clients, BSI is one of the world's largest certification bodies.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] It audits and provides certification to companies worldwide who implement management systems standards.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] BSI also runs training courses that cover the implementation and auditing requirements of national and international management systems standards.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] BSI's best known product in the UK is the Kitemark, a registered certification mark first used in 1903.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] The Kitemark – which is recognized by 82% of UK adults – signifies products or services which have been assessed and tested as meeting the requirements of the related specification or standard within a Kitemark scheme.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing of products for a range of certifications, including for CE marking.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] CE marking must be applied to a wide range of products intended for sale in the European Economic Area.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] Frequently, manufacturers or importers need a third-party certification of their product from an accredited or 'Notified' body.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] BSI holds Notified Body status for 15 EU Directives, including construction products, marine equipment, pressurized equipment and personal protective equipment.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing for manufacturers developing new products and has facilities to test across a wide range of sectors, including construction, fire safety, electrical and electronic and engineering products.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] BSI provides regulatory and quality management reviews and product certification for medical device manufacturers in the Worldwide.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] It is the market leader in the US, the world's biggest healthcare market.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI Group, with support from the Construction Products Association, led the development of a product identification and traceability system known as *BSI Identify*.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] The initiative responded to recommendations made by Dame Judith Hackitt following her review of building safety, which called for wider adoption of permanent product marking and consistent labelling systems to improve traceability across the built environment sector.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] BSI Identify uses new Digital Object Identifier (DOI) technology "to deliver a unique, constant, and interoperable identifier", known as a BSI UPIN, "which can be assigned to products to help UK manufacturers to directly manage information about their products in the supply chain".
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] The aim of the BSI Identify programme is that "wherever you are with [a] product, you can take a snapshot of the QR code with your mobile device, and it will immediately take you to the product technical data sheet.
[src:asc-x9/bsi-group] The BSI coat of arms was granted by the College of Arms in 1951.
